6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Paradex's hourly funding provides 8x more arbitrage opportunities compared to Phemex's standard 8-hour intervals. The DEX structure means funding rates reflect pure supply-demand without exchange intervention. Phemex's longer intervals create larger rate movements but fewer capture windows. Portfolio margin on Paradex enables more capital-efficient strategies across positions. Both exchanges use mark price indexing but Paradex's StarkNet settlement introduces additional gas considerations."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange has better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Paradex offers 8x more frequent funding payments at 1-hour intervals versus Phemex's 8-hour standard. However, Phemex has deeper liquidity and lower maker fees at 0.01% versus Paradex's 0.02%."},{"question":"How do custody models affect funding strategies?","answer":"Paradex's self-custodial DEX eliminates counterparty risk but requires StarkNet gas for settlements. Phemex's centralized model offers instant settlements and portfolio netting but introduces exchange risk."},{"question":"Which platform has lower total trading costs?","answer":"Phemex has lower maker fees (0.01% vs 0.02%) but higher taker fees (0.06% vs 0.05%). Paradex adds StarkNet gas costs but eliminates withdrawal fees for on-chain positions."},{"question":"How do margin systems compare for arbitrage?","answer":"Paradex's portfolio margin allows cross-margining between spot and perps positions for better capital efficiency. Phemex uses traditional isolated and cross-margin without portfolio optimization features."}]}]
